Lobi Traore - The Lobi Traore Group
2005

Raw and feral blues. Another gem from Mali.

Brought to you by TQMP
The Quality Music Project

Guitarist Lobi TraorÃƒï¿½Ã‚Â¹ plays deep blues from his homeland in Mali, east of that other River of Song -- the Niger. He is not as famous as the late Ali Farka Toure, his countryman and grand influence on much of Mali's music (and who actually produced TraorÃƒï¿½Ã‚Â¹'s 1994 set, Bamako, named for the country's capitol). TraorÃƒï¿½Ã‚Â¹ was the guitarist on Damon Albarn's Mali Music recording that kicked off the Honest Jons label that this recording is released on. The blurb on this boasts a BBC review that positions TraorÃƒï¿½Ã‚Â¹ somewhere between Jimmy Page and John Lee Hooker. Forget it. TraorÃƒï¿½Ã‚Â¹'s guitar playing is utterly electric, gritty, funky, and knotty. His style is raw but extremely sophisticated. Check out the opener, &quot;Jugu,&quot; with its killer polyrhythms and TraorÃƒï¿½Ã‚Â¹'s throaty baritone spitting out the lyrics. His fills cover the breadth and depth of the rhythm section's furious playing. The distortion has nothing to do with sound effects, man -- he's playing it at ten! The following cut, &quot;Deni Kelen Be Koko,&quot; feels a lot like something that should be on Fat Possum if they did a field recording in Mali. There is so much here that is steaming, tough, and wiry. This is the best blues record of early 2006 and it isn't even a blues record. It's hard Malian folk music gone electric, and full of the most killer singing, dancing, and yes, guitar playing out there.
-- allmusic.com

